<li id="cite_note-24"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-24">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1133582631"><cite id="CITEREFAndrews" class="citation web cs1">Andrews, Peter. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.photoscientia.co.uk/Gamma.htm">"The Monitor calibration and Gamma assessment page"</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">2018-11-30</span></span>. <q>the problem is caused by the risetime of most monitor hardware not being sufficiently fast to turn from full black to full white in the space of a single pixel, or even two, in some cases.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=The+Monitor+calibration+and+Gamma+assessment+page&amp;rft.aulast=Andrews&amp;rft.aufirst=Peter&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.photoscientia.co.uk%2FGamma.htm&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AGamma+correction" class="Z3988"></span></span>
